Abstract
With the growing popularity of surveillance cameras, surveillance
cameras have been widely installed in diﬀerent places. A fundamental
task for a distributed multi-camera surveillance system is person re-
identiﬁcation (ReID) which is deﬁned as a task that aims to associate
people across camera views at diﬀerent locations and time. Recently,
this problem is currently receiving increasing attention from computer
vision researchers thanks to its applications in many ﬁelds of the life
like as human computer interaction, intelligent video analytic.
Despite encouraging progress obtained over the years, person ReID
remains open research topic due to its challenges. Fusion techniques
with the aim to leverage the discriminative power of diﬀerent appear-
ance features for person representation has been widely applied in
person re-identiﬁcation. The fusion are normally performed by con-
catenating all feature vectors (known as early fusion) or by combining
matching scores of diﬀerent fusion (known as late fusion). Previous
studies have proved that late fusion techniques achieve better results
than early fusion ones. However, majority of the studies focus on
determining the suitable weighting schemes that can reﬂect the role
of each feature. The determined weights are then integrated in con-
ventional similarity functions, such as Cosine. This thesis presents a
robust person re-identiﬁcation method by combining the metric learn-
ing and late fusion techniques. The metric learning method Cross-
view Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (XQDA) is employed to learn
a discriminant low dimensional subspace to minimize the intra-person
distance while maximize the inter-person distance. Moreover, product
rule-based and sum rule-based late fusion techniques are applied on
these distances. Three state-of-the-art features that are GOG (Gaus-
sians of Gaussians), LOMO (Local Maximal Occurrence) and deep-
learned features extracted through a Residual network (ResNet) are
used to represent the person appearance. The experimental results on
PRID 2011 show that the proposed method obtains +2.4%, +8.2%
and +9.6% of improvement over the best results obtained with the
single feature when using all frames, frames in a walking cycle and 4
keyframes respectively. When working with more challenging dataset
that is iLIDS-VID, the proposed method increases the accuracy at
rank 1 by 10.7%, 13.4% and 8.4% for all frames, frames in a walking
cycle and 4 keyframes.

Chapter 1
Introduction
1.1 Motivations
We are living in technology era when the development of industry 4.0 when the
demand about person recognition ability of machine is higher. Nowadays, with
the development of many modern camera productions as well as new technologies,
surveillance cameras have been widely installed in diﬀerent places. To leverage
ample information coming from these cameras, intelligent video analytic has at-
tracted a lot of attention from research community as well as industry.
Person re-identiﬁcation (or person Re-id for short) is deﬁned as the problem
of matching people across camera views in a multi-camera system. It brings
many useful applications for public security device development such as intelligent
camera surveillance system. In real-world application, a person, or a watch-list of
a handful of known people, is considered as a target to search in a large volume
of video surveillance footsteps that people on the watch-list have the ability to
reappear. A list of cropped images of people is retrieved as candidates (or may be
called ”ﬁltered results”) and hopefully they contain people who desire to own the
same identity for search target. Although, there have been a numerous approaches

multi-shot ones. In single-shot person ReID, each person has only one sole image

from realistic applications because of insuﬃcient information. Therefore, most
of person ReID works have paid attention on multi-shot person ReID, in which
each person is represented by image sequences. Obviously, in comparison with
single-shot, multi-shot approach can get richer information and can achieve higher
performance.

1.2 Challenges
Beside opportunities that are aforementioned, person ReID has to face with many
challenges. Firstly, images that are captured by diﬀerent cameras might lead to
diﬀerences in color can drastically aﬀect the performance of the model. Fur-
thermore, the illumination, background clutter, occlusion, partial observation of
human body and dynamic posture of the person are usually dramatically diﬀerent
which might easily fool the algorithm and render it unusable. Figure 1.3 shows
the images of the same person captured by two diﬀerent cameras in PRID-2011

1.3 Objective and contributions
As I mention above, the research aims at improving the performance of person
re-identiﬁcation. Recently, researchers have introduced many approaches for the
improvement of person ReID’s performance. However, the person ReID perfor-
mance is still low, this leads to the limitation of the application of person ReID
in the reality. The main objective of the thesis is to propose fusion method for
person ReID. Fusion techniques with the aim to leverage the discriminative power
of diﬀerent appearance features for person representation has been widely applied
in person re-identiﬁcation. The fusion are normally performed by concatenating
all feature vectors (known as early fusion) or by combining matching scores of
diﬀerent fusion (known as late fusion). Previous studies have proved that late
fusion techniques achieve better results than early fusion ones. However, major-

Chapter 2
State of the Art
There are many approaches that have been introduced for person re-identiﬁcation
problem. Most existing algorithms for person re-identiﬁcation deal with feature
extraction, metric learning or a combination of both. While feature extraction
aims to extract robust features that can reﬂect appearance of person’s images,
metric learning consists of diﬀerent methods that are able to measure eﬀectively
the similarity between images. This chapter aims at analyzing the state-of-the-art
method for person re-identiﬁcation. Beside two important methods mentioned
above, a noteworthy discussed aspects in this ﬁeld are person representation,
person matching as well as feature fusion.
2.1 Feature extraction at image level
In person re-identiﬁcation, diﬀerent researches use a wide variety of features, these
diﬀerences depend on purposes that each researcher wants to achieve. This section
explains typical widely used features in many research works in re-identiﬁcation
ﬁeld. Basing on method as well as design structure of each type of features, we
can divide these features extraction method into 2 type: Hand-crafted features
6
2.1 Feature extraction at image level
and Deep learning-base features
2.1.1 Hand-crafted features
Hand-crafted features refer to properties derived using various algorithms using
the information present in the image itself. The design of hand-crafted features
often involves ﬁnding the right trade-oﬀ between accuracy and computational ef-
ﬁciency. The following features are some hand-crafted features which are popular
used in person Re-ID in order to illustrate the robustness and eﬀectively perfor-
mance of each type of features in this problem.
gBiCov [3]: gBiCov is proposed to deal with the challenge of background and
illumination variations. The main idea of this method is the combination of Bi-
ologically Inspired Features (BIF) and Covariance descriptors. This descriptor is
generated by calculating and encoding the diﬀerence between BIF features at dif-
ferent scales. The distance between two persons can then be eﬃciently measured
by computing the Euclidean distance of their signatures, avoiding some time con-
suming operations in Riemannian manifold required by the use of Covariance
descriptors.
Figure 2.1: Flowchart of the gBiCov representation [3]
The gBiCoV features generation progress is illustrated on Fig. 2.1. Person’s
image ﬁrst is divided into 3 color channels through HSV color space. These input
images are convoluted with Gabor ﬁlters at diﬀerent scales, and the similar scales
are grouped into bands. In next step, by using the max operator within the same
7
2.1 Feature extraction at image level
band of the Gabor features, we can get the BIF Magnitude Images which are next
divided into small regions thanks to convariance descriptors. Finally, the diﬀer-
ence of covariance descriptors between the corresponding regions of the diﬀerent
bands are calculated and then concatenated to form the ﬁnal representation of
the image.

tation. the mentioned machine learning algorithm is AdaBoost, this method can
combined diﬀerent kinds of simple features into a single similarity function.

DenseColorSIFT[12]: Stems from the require to solve problems surrounding
the limitations of the previous supervised approaches in handling the hidden of
person’s salient information, this representation method is proposed as a novel
perspective for person re-identiﬁcation based on unsupervised salience learning
where distinctive features are extracted without requiring identity labels in the
training progress. In [12], the authors ﬁrst apply adjacency constrained patch
matching which is utilized with adjacency constraint for handling the misalign-
ment problem caused by viewpoint change, pose variation and articulation to
build dense correspondence between image pairs, which shows eﬀectiveness in
handling misalignment caused by large viewpoint and pose variations. In the
next step, human salience is learned in an unsupervised manner, incorporated in
patch matching to ﬁnd reliable and discriminative matched patches in order to
improve the performance in person re-identiﬁcation task.
DenseColorSIFT feature vector, denoted as dColorSIFT, is the combination of
the Dense Color Histogram and Dense SIFT. For histogram, each person image is
9
2.1 Feature extraction at image level
densely divided into a grid of local patch where a LAB color histogram is extracted
from each patch and computed on the downsampled scales for robustly capture
color information. Beside, all the histogram are L2 normalized in order to the
purpose the combination with other features. The histogram is also integrated
the SIFT descriptor as a complementary feature in order to handle viewpoint and
illumination change with the similar setting of dense color histogram extracting.
A dense grid of patches are also sampled on each human image before divided into
4 x 4 cells, quantize the orientations of local gradients into 8 bins, and obtain a 4
x 4 x 8 = 128 dimentional SIFT feature. SIFT features are also L2 normalized.
In the concatenation stage, the parameters of feature extraction are as follows:
patches of size 10 x 10 pixels are sampled on a dense grid with a grid step size
4; 32-bin color histograms are computed in L, A, B channels respectively, and in
each channel, 3 levels of downsampling are used with scaling factors 0.5, 0.75 and
1; SIFT features are also extracted in 3 color channels and thus produces a 128 x
3 feature vector for each patch. Conclusion, each patch is ﬁnally represented by
a discriminative descriptor vector with length 32 x 3 x 3 + 128 x 3 = 672.

to generate a global representation of an image. Though the experience on two
popular person re-identiﬁcation benchmarks (VIPeR and ETHZ), the obtained
Local Descriptors achieved positive performances.

LOMO (Local Maximal Occurrence) [4]: Another person’s image repre-
sentation which is used in experiment result section of this report called Local
Maximal Occurrence method, proposed by Liao at al.[4]. The main task in this
method is analyzing the horizontal occurrence of local features, and maximizing
the occurrence to make a stable representation against viewpoint changes. Fur-
thermore, the Retinex transform and a scale invariant texture operator is also
integrated in order to deal with the illumination variations.
GOG [14]: Gaussians of Gaussians (GOG) is a novel descriptor based on hier-
archical Gaussian distribution of pixel features which is proposed in [14]. This
method is proposed in order to solve the problem about the absent of the mean
information of pixel features and using both means and covariances are included
in their parameters. As a result, this new descriptor can model both the mean
and the covariance information of a pixel features properly. To compute GOG
feature, ﬁrstly, an image of a person is devided into regions. Then, with each
region, the local patches densely is extracted before described based on Gaussian
distribution of pixel features. In the next step, each of patch Gaussians is ﬂat-
tened and vectorized by considering the underlining geometry of Gaussians. The
11
2.1 Feature extraction at image level
authors then summarized the patch Gaussians inside a region into a region Gaus-
sians in order to generate a feature vector. Finally, the feature vectors extracted
from all regions are concatenated into one vector. This feature representation
method is also discussed for the proposed method in the next chapter.
2.1.2 Deep learning-based features
Diﬀerent from hand-crafted features, deep learning based approaches focus on de-
signing a descriptor where we can conﬁgure the most optimal function as well as
the appropriate deep learning network structures that making the change of the
descriptor to obtain the most eﬀectively features. Diﬀerent network architectures
have been proposed for person re-identiﬁcation [15]. In [16], ResNet is intro-
duced as a method of representation that based on the applications of residual
learning framework in order to ease the training of network that are substan-
tially deeper than those used previously. The authors develop the layers through
learning residual functions with reference to the layer inputs, instead of learning
unreferenced functions. As a result, the achievements which are veriﬁed by ex-
perience progress is the ease of optimization and the augmentation of accuracy
from considerably increased depth. This improvement overcomes the VGG net
about the simplicity in spite of deeper architecture in ImageNet dataset. In this
report, ResNet is also used for the framework construction as well as experiment
so the detailed description will be mentioned in chapter 3. The authors in [17]
made a comparison between hand-crafted and deep learning features to build an
eﬀective descriptor called Feature Fusion Network (FNN). Meanwhile, Cheng et
al.[18] introduced a multi-channel CNN model (MCCNN) that learns both global
full-body and local part features. The features are integrated to generate a ﬁnal
signature for each person image.
12
2.2 Person representation in multi-shot person ReID
2.2 Person representation in multi-shot person
ReID
Diﬀerent from the single-shot one, multi-shot person re-identiﬁcation approach
exploits richer information and often achieves higher accuracy in person represen-
tation task thanks to its multiple images for person ReID. However, multi-shot
ReID approach has its own challenges. The ﬁrst challenge is the high number
of images captured for each individual in a camera view point which lead to a
large storage resources and computational time consuming. Furthermore, using
all images of a person making superabundance and ineﬃciency for person repre-
sentation.
To get a person representation from multiple images of the same person in
multi-shot person re-identiﬁcation, some work propose to extract spatial-temporal
descriptors while the others try to learn an uniﬁed feature for each person. In the
ﬁrst approach, both spatial and temporal information are provided to improve the
matching rate [19],[20], [21], [22]. The constraint between spatial and temporal
information is a basis to ﬁnd a true matching sets. Bedagkar et al. [19] provide
a method to extract facial and color features and to generate a novel spatial-
temporal model. This model is learned for employing in both open and closed set
matching. Hadjkacem et al. [21] propose a spatio-temporal covariance descriptor
with an integrated time parameter for representing a sequence of images. The
main contribution of this work is to encode the motion information, added to
appearance features to generate a spatio-temporal covariance matrix represent
a sequence of images. Unlike the previous works that computes features on all
images of a person, Liu et al. in [20] propose to extract a walking cycle and
process only images in this cycle. This algorithm can reduce the complexity and
computation time. However, in surveillance camera network, a person is normally
13
2.2 Person representation in multi-shot person ReID
observed by diﬀerent viewpoints. A descriptor, extracted from a person walking
cycle, is not always enough to provide the signature for a given image sequence.
Chen et al. [22] introduce a new spatial-temporal feature, called Optical Flow
Energy Image (OFEI), which refers to human body parts or carry-on objects
which are stable regions over a sequence of frames at distinct times and loca-
tions. Further more, appearance and spatial-temporal features are integrated to
increase the performance of this method. In [23], the authors proposed to extract
GOG features from representative frames that are four keyframes and frames in
a walking cycle for multi-shot person representation.
Another way to generate the ﬁnal person representation from an image se-
quence is to use the RNN (Recurrent Neural Network) or its variant. In this way,
the RNN structure determines what features are kept through an image sequence
[24], [25], [26]. Yan et al. [24] get the information from an image sequence by
provide a feature vector of each image to an LSTM (Long Short Term Memory)
unit. An LSTM unit is a type of RNN (Recurrent Neural Network), which has a
recurrent structure. The LSTM unit is able to decide whether to keep the existing
memory via introduced gates. If it detects an important feature from an input
sequence, it determine to carry this information over a long distance. By using
LSTM units, the important information of each image sequence is retained. This
lead to increase the matching rate in case of video-based person re-identiﬁcation.
A deep recurrent convolutional network is introduced by McLaughlin et al.[25]
and Wu et al. [26], which consists of recurrent layer, and temporal pooling to
produce an improved video representation. In these work, CNN features are ex-
tracted on each frame and given to the RNN structures and temporal pooling
layers to represent an image sequence as a single feature vector. To leverage the
advantages of both hand-crafted and deep learning features, in [27], the authors
have extracted GOG features and fed it to RFA network presented in [24].
14
2.3 Person matching
2.3 Person matching
Person matching is considered as an important stage in a person re-identiﬁcation
pipeline. The main task of this stage is matching images of a person across
multiple camera views by calculating distance between images or sequence images
that are used to represent the person. It is worth to note that the distance can
be directly computed by applying Cosine or Euclidean distance [24]. However, a
huge number of the person ReID methods employ metric learning in order to learn
a metric that reﬂects the visual camera to camera transitions allowing for a more
powerful classiﬁcation. As same as other aspects of Re-ID ﬁeld, there are variety
of matching methods which achieve diﬀerent results. Besides a discriminative and
robust descriptor, an eﬀective metric for person matching also contributes to the
eﬃciency of person Re-ID. This section aim of introducing some metric learning
approaches proposed for person matching.
Mahalanobis metric learning is the most widely used metric learning method
in person ReID. This method has shown good performance for diverse visual
classication tasks as well as specic methods that have been developed for the task
of person re-identication [28], [29]. Given n data points x

These aforementioned metric learning methods have problem when working
with large scale datasets and require to specify fully supervised labels for all data

in form of equivalence constraints. In [34], the authors proposed Keep It Simple
and Straight forward Metric (KISSME) method that learn an eﬀective metric just
based on equivalence constraints.
An extension of KISSME approaches to cross-view metric learning called
Cross-view Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (XQDA) is also applied in this thesis
as a main metric learning method for the proposed framework in order to duel
with the view point change and cross-view matching problem. The deﬁnition by
detail of this method is mentioned in the next chapter.
2.4 Feature fusion
To leverage the robustness of diﬀerent features for person representation in person
ReID, some eﬀorts have tried to combine several features. This strategy, named
feature fusion, has been widely applied in various research ﬁelds, such as video
16
2.4 Feature fusion
annotation. In literature, there have been impressive works focused on combining
diﬀerent kinds of features to achieve a higher improvement in person ReID task.
We can divide these approaches into two manners of feature-level (early fusion)
and score-level fusion (late fusions). For early feature fusion, the combination is
conducted at feature level, the extracted features are concatenated to generate
a larger dimensional feature. Whereas, late fusion scheme combines features at
score-level.
Gao et al. [35] suggested an eﬀective combination of high-dimensional and
low-level features before Wu et al. [17] realized that CNN features only work
well on large datasets which have enough training images. Therefore, the authors
provided a method to combine both hand-crafted features and deeply learned
features to take advantages of each. Xin et al.[36] proposed to mix the distri-
bution of color, texture and edge features. The experiments on some datasets
proved that it decreased signiﬁcantly complexity of computation without using
image segmentation step. The advantages of early fusion is to be easy to com-
bine features to create a ﬁnal feature to represent an image. However, the early
fusion methods do not evaluate the eﬀectiveness of a feature because of process-
ing concurrently. On the other hand, in late fusion, a score is generated after
matching process corresponding to a given feature. Based on this score, the ﬁnal
similarity function is constructed to measure the distance between two images or
image sequences. Eisenbach et al.[37] proved that late fusion methods can achieve
better results than early fusion ones. Lejbolle et al.[38] divided a human-body
image into three diﬀerent parts, including head, torso and legs. Three features
at diﬀerent abstraction levels are extracted on each part. They are then fused
at score-level to improve the accuracy of person Re-ID. The advantage of this
method is to divide the human-body into parts to avoid misalignment matching.
Unlike the previous works in which features are weighted with the constant value,
17
2.5 Conclusions
Zheng et al. [8] proposed a method to fuse features in adaptive manner in both
image search and person Re-ID problems.
2.5 Conclusions
In this chapter, I have analyzed in detail state-of-the-art methods for person ReID
in which I focused on the feature extraction, metric learning and feature fusion
techniques. As we can see in this chapter, numerous methods have been proposed
for person ReID and remarkable improvements have been obtained. However, the
obtained performances of state-of-the-art person ReID methods sill need to be
improved in order to apply in real application. In the next chapter, the proposed
method that combines late fusion and metric learning for multi-shot person ReID
will be described.

3.2.1 Walking cycle extraction
A walking cycle, is also known as a gait cycle, is deﬁned as the interval between
two consecutive heel-strike (HS) events of the same foot. The duration of a gait
cycle is known as stride time. Gait is further characterized by the instants at
which a foot leaves the ground and starts swinging forward: this is known as
a toe-oﬀ (TO) event (some works refer to heel-strike and toe-oﬀ as initial foot
contact and ﬁnal foot contact, respectively). For each leg, a walking cycle is
characterized by two phases: stance (leg support, lasting from HS to TO) and
swing (leg swinging forward, lasting from TO to the next HS), illustrated in Fig.
3.2. There exists several methods for extracting walking cycles form an image
sequence. In this thesis, the walking cycle extraction method was based on FEP
(Flow Energy Proﬁle). Firstly, given an image sequence Q = (S

3.3.1 GOG features extraction
Gaussian of Gaussian (GOG) is one of the most eﬀective features description
method for ReID problem [14]. The reason I choose this type of feature for per-
son representation because it provides a conceptually simple and consistent way
to generate discriminative and robust features that describe color and textural
information simultaneously. The idea of this method is based on hierarchical
Gaussian distribution of pixel-level features. It contains both mean and covari-
ance information that are crucial signatures for the recognition progress. The
extraction process of an image is presented of Fig. 3.4. In the ﬁrst step, images
are proceeded as the input of the color-space transformation which converts an
RGB image to another color-space one (Lab, HSV, nRnG). Next, image is di-
vided into N overlapping horizontal regions and local patches with the size of
(k × k) pixels are densely extracted. Basing on the output of the previous step
(extracted feature vectors at pixel level), we generate the features for patch and
region. Finally, the region features are concatenated to form a unique signature
for a person image. GOG feature vectors are extracted on the four diﬀerent color
spaces, called GOG

3.3.3 Local Maximal Occurrence features (LOMO)
The LOMO feature is ﬁrstly introduced in [4]. To compute LOMO feature for a
person image, ﬁrst sliding technique is applied. Specically, a sub-window with the
size of 10 × 10, with an overlapping step of 5 pixels is used. Within each subwin-
dow, two scales of SILTP histograms and an 8×8×8-bin joint HSV histogram are
computed where each histogram bin represents the occurrence probability of one
pattern in a subwindow. To address viewpoint changes, the authors proposed to
check all subwindows at the same horizontal location, and maximize the local oc-
currence of each pattern (i.e. the same histogram bin) among these subwindows.
Therefore, the obtained histogram is invariant to viewpoint changes and and at
the same time allows to capture local region characteristics of a person. Figure 3.7
illustrates the process to extracting LOMO feature from a person image. I also
use LOMO for person representation because it can make a stable representation
against viewpoint changes as well as handle illumination variations by applying
the Retinex transform and the Scale Invariant Local Ternary Pattern (SILTP).

Chapter 4
Experimental Results
Overview
This chapter presents the experimental results of the proposed approach. To
evaluate the performance of the proposed method, two benchmark datasets that
are PRID 2011 [2] and ILIDs-VID [5] are used.
4.1 Datasets and metrics
4.1.1 PRID-2011 dataset
The PRID-2011 is ﬁrstly introduced in [2]. This is widely used in the state-
of-the-art methods. With the main purpose is create a test data for person
re-identiﬁcation approaches, this dataset consists of images extracted from mul-
tiple person trajectories recorded from two diﬀerent, static surveillance cameras.
Images from these cameras vary in perspective and diﬀer signiﬁcantly in lighting,
background and camera characteristics. These images are extracted from trajec-
tories so that several diﬀerent poses per person are available in each camera view
with the resolution of each image is 128x64. there are 475 person trajectories are
34
4.1 Datasets and metrics
Figure 4.1: Camera view point of PRID 2011 dataset [2].
Figure 4.2: Person’s images from two diﬀerent cameras in PRID 2011 dataset [2].
recorded from one view and 856 from the other one, with 245 persons appearing
in both views. In which, some person images which have heavily occluded or less
than ﬁve reliable images in each camera view, as well as corrupted are ﬁltered
out by tracking and annotation errors.
PRID-2011 dataset had two versions, one representing the single-shot scenario
and one representing the multi-shot scenario. The multi-shot version contains
multiple images per person (at least ﬁve per camera view). The exact number
depends on a person’s walking path and speed as well as occlusions. The single-
shot version contains just one (randomly selected) image per person trajectory,
i.e., one image from view A and one image from view B.

4.1 Datasets and metrics
Figure 4.3: Person images from two diﬀerent cameras of iLIDS-VID dataset [5].
4.1.2 iLIDS-VID
The iLIDS-VID dataset [5] was created from the pedestrians observed in two non-
overlapping camera views from the i-LIDS Multiple-Camera Tracking Scenario
(MCTS) dataset which was captured at an airport arrival hall under a multi-
camera CCTV network (see Fig. 4.3). hlIt contains 600 image sequences of 300
distinct individuals, with one pair of image sequences from two camera views for
each person and the resolution of each image is 128x64. Each image sequence has
variable length ranging from 23 to 192 image frames, with an average number
of 73. The clothing similarities among people, lighting and viewpoint variations
across camera views, cluttered background and random occlusions made many
challenges and problems for this dataset.
4.1.3 Cumulative Matching Characteristic curve (CMC
curve)
There are a variety of metrics that are proposed for quantifying the eﬀectiveness
of a re-identiﬁcation method. The most common metric is CMC curve. Given
a probe person, a ranked list of persons in gallery set is returned. Then, CMC
curve measures the chance of the true match appearing in the top 1, 2 and N
of ranked list. The ﬁrst point of CMC curve is the Rank-1 accuracy. Besides
36
4.2 Experimental results on PRID-2011
Rank-1 accuracy, the accuracies at some important ranks such as 5, 10,15 and 20
are usually reported.
4.2 Experimental results on PRID-2011

all frames are shown on Figures 4.4, 4.5 and 4.6 respectively, setting all weights

From the results, we can see that among three features, independent feature of

respectively. It is worth noting that the results of GOG are the results of the

the highest result, at 77.20%, followed by the result of ResNet and LOMO, with

seem to be better with 86.80% in comparison with the sum-rule approach with
86.77%. Beside, in comparison with the four key frames case, with more selected

the best result belonged to GOG with 79.10%. Beside, the matching rate of

slightly better than that of sum-rule one, with 87.26% of accuracy compared to
87.15%.

4.4 Discussions
The above-mentioned experimental results are compared with several existing
works on person ReID in Table 4.2, with two best results are in bold. In this Table,
the matching rates at the most important ranks of 1, 5 and 20 are reported. It is
worth to note that the reported results from work [23] was conducted by running
provided source code. From this Table, we realize that our proposal outperforms
the other works even compared with the most recent work of Nguyen et al. [23].
In case of using all frames, the matching rates obtained with fusion schemes would
be approximate to those in [23]. However, for using four key frames or walking
cycle, the matching rates at rank-1 increased up to 9.6% and 8.2% on PRID-2011
and 20.7% and 20.0% on iLIDS-VID, respectively. These achievements again
conﬁrm the eﬀectiveness of fusion schemes for person ReID problem.
4.5 Conclusions
This chapter presented the experimental results of the proposed method on two
datasets. The obtained results have shown that the proposed method with diﬀer-
ent fusion schemes on 3 type of features allows to improve signiﬁcantly the ReID
performance.

Chapter 5
Conclusions and future works
5.1 Conclusions
In the master course program, I have achieved more knowledge about computer
vision in general and person re-identiﬁcation problem in particular. I also have
the knowledge about annotation progress, machine learning algorithm, image
processing technology, combination features as well as veriﬁcation from training to
testing model. Our idea, from the purpose taking advantages of diﬀerent features
that are LOMO, GOG and ResNet, using late fusion schemes with product-
rule-based and sum-rule-base for multi-shot person ReID in order to improve its
performance has shown the potential in person re-identiﬁcation problem. The
experiments conducted on two common-used benchmark datasets of PRID-2011
and iLIDS-VID with remarkable results. The experimental results on PRID 2011
show that the proposed method obtains +2.4%, +8.2% +9.6% of improvement
over the best results obtained with the single feature when using all frames,
frames in a walking cycle and 4 keyframes respectively. When working with
more challenging dataset that is iLIDS-VID, the proposed method increases the
accuracy at rank1 by 10.7%, 13.4% and 8.4% for all frames, frames in a walking
cycle and 4 keyframes. The obtained results of the thesis has been reported
in one paper accepted for presenting in the third International Conference on

5.2 Future works
Due to the limitation of duration of the thesis, the experiments have conducted
on two datasets in order to verify the eﬃciency of the proposed method. There
are still a lot of works that I would like to continue for this project in which can
be categorized as follows:
• In the future, I would like to evaluate the proposed method with others
person ReID datasets;
• In this fusion schemes of this thesis, the feature weights are predeﬁned.
However, each feature may have diﬀerent role for each query person. In
the future, I would like to investigate diﬀerent weighting scheme including
query adaptive late fusion presented for single shot in [48] and for multi-shot
in [49].
• The experimental results have conﬁrmed that using more features can help
to improve the person ReID accuracy. However, it also requires more com-
putational time and may not ensure the real-time requirement of person
ReID. In the future, diﬀerent parallel strategies will be investigated in or-
der to increase the person ReID response time.
• The proposed method have treated images of a person independently. This
means that the temporal aspect is not exploited in the proposed method.
45
5.2 Future works
Therefore, in the future, I would like to investigate temporal aspect in order
to improve person ReID performance.
